The Lakeland CSD Food Service Department is excited to announce that due to a temporary waiver all Lakeland children under the age of 18 are eligible to pick up FREE breakfast and lunches while learning remotely!

These meals can be ordered weekly on the district website at www.lakelandschools.org To further accommodate our families we have extended our Monday pick up hours to 11am-4:30pm. If you cannot pick up your meals between these hours please call (914)603-9054 to arrange for an alternate pick up.

Free/Reduced Meal applications still need to be submitted and can be done online at MySchoolApps.com

Thank you for your participation in the Thoughtexchange project on reentry. We encourage anyone who hasn’t shared their thoughts to participate. The deadline is midnight Monday, July 13, 2020. To access the Thoughtexchange, please click: my.thoughtexchange.com/#309679837
If you have already participated, please feel free to visit again to share more thoughts and/or rate thoughts that you may not have seen before.

When participating, please keep the following in mind:

The exchange is confidential. Your thoughts will be shared, but not your identity.
Please be polite and respectful as you share and rate thoughts.
If you see a thought that is rude, hurtful or identifies a person or group, you can report it by clicking in the upper right corner of the thought.

Thank you again for participating and sharing your thoughts to help our school communities and our region best plan for a smooth and successful reentry.

Dr. Brendan Lyons
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
As I prepare to move on to my next chapter, I want to take this opportunity to thank the entire Lakeland Community for everything given to my family and me, and to everyone who worked so hard to see us be the best we could be. While far from perfect, we have made tremendous strides in the past ten years, and I am very proud of everyone and everything we accomplished. I also want to thank the Board of Education members who gave me the opportunity, supported me, and worked hand in hand to develop and implement our mission, vision, and core beliefs. Also, to our entire staff and in particular, my secretary, Lynn, who after my family, was my closest and most important advisor. She made sure we never stopped working hard and always doing our best.

I leave all of you with a short video I made for our seniors but really for the entire Lakeland Community. It expresses how I feel and what I wish for every one of you.

On behalf of my family, Thank you for everything.
George E. Stone, Ed.D.

Kindness is contagious. The rink is closed, but that doesn’t stop these students. The Lakeland/Panas Varsity Hockey Rebels players inspired the Lakeland/Panas Modified Rebels Hockey team to do good. The majority of the L/P Modified Rebels Hockey team joined Joe Riggio, Colin Vaughn, and Ryan Vogel, representing Walter Panas High School and the Varsity Hockey Rebels to donate again to the local homeless shelter Jan Peek, Peekskill. Through their combined efforts, the players donated baked goods, dinner, and much needed toiletries.
Modified players:
Marc Moccia
Michael Alfinito
Shannon Adler
Matthew Pushkin
Sean VanRiper
Maya Montalvo
Justin Seidman
Ryan Rosenbaum
Kai McCarron
Varsity Players:
Joe Riggio - Walter Panas Freshman
Colin Vaughn - Walter Panas Sophomore
Ryan Vogel - Walter Panas Sophomore

The Westchester County Department of Parks, Recreation and Conservation would like to work with our local public schools to employ our youth this summer. Westchester County Parks is in the process of hiring 200 Lifeguards and 75 Cashiers, Laborers, and Social Distancing Monitors (classified as Recreation Attendants). We have positions available in our Pools, Beaches and Park Facilities throughout the county. Lifeguards are in high demand at Saxon Woods Park Pool, Sprain Ridge Park Pool, Tibbetts Brook Park Pool & Wilson Woods Park Pool. For your convenience, I have attached the job descriptions, rate of pay and an application for employment. Below, please find a link that leads to the Job Opportunities page on the Westchester County Website. All pertinent information and applications can be found there.

LAKELAND SALUTES THE CLASS OF 2020
A parade to celebrate the Graduating Class of 2020 from Walter Panas and Lakeland High Schools was held Saturday, June 6, 2020 at the Jefferson Valley Mall.
https://events.locallive.tv/events/38093
Graduates from both schools were able to drive around the mall in their decorated vehicle led by a police escort and cheered on by parents, staff members, and friends. The celebration parade continued down Route 6, where friends, family, and business' cheered the graduates. Special thanks to the parents of WPHS and LHS for organizing the event and to the Jefferson Valley Mall, Yorktown Police Department, and Westchester County Police for all their assistance.

post_text:
BUDGET VOTE FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

1. I have to sign the ballot envelope. How will my vote be anonymous?
The folded ballots will be removed from the envelopes and placed in a separate anonymous ballot box and the envelopes placed in another. The ballots will be counted with no envelopes attached and will remain completely anonymous.

2. Why am I getting a ballot from the Lakeland Central School District and the Yorktown School District?
We cannot control the voter lists we receive from Westchester County, but we have a listing of all Lakeland addresses. each return address is checked to ensure it lies within the Lakeland boundaries. If a non-resident completes a ballot and returns it to us it will not be counted.

BUDGET AND TRUSTEE VOTE JUNE 9

* The absentee ballots for the school elections are being sent directly from the printer and were mailed to residents via USPS today, Friday, May 29th. They should arrive in the next few days.

* Please complete and return them as quickly as possible.
They can be returned via USPS or placed in a secured ballot box located outside of the gymnasium at Van Cortlandtville Elementary School, 3100 E. Main St. (Route 6), Lake Mohegan. This is Lakeland's annual voting location.

* All ballots must be returned by 5:00 pm Tuesday, June 9, 2020.

* PLEASE NOTE: THE SCHOOL BUDGET AND TRUSTEE BALLOT IS SEPARATE AND DIFFERENT FROM THE JUNE 23rd PRIMARY ELECTION BALLOT. THESE ARE TWO SEPARATE ELECTIONS

* June 9th is the School District Budget and Trustee Vote, June 23rd is the Democratic Primary Vote.

Thank you for your understanding as we try to meet the Governor's Executive Order.

Dr. George E. Stone
Lakeland Central School District
gstone@lakelandschools.org

post_text:
One of Lakeland's Finest-Matthew Swift, Walter Panas Class of 2014

Matthew Swift, Walter Panas Alum, Class of 2014, is an engineer for SpaceEx. Matthew in collaboration with a team of engineers conceptualized and designed the world's first reusable orbital rocket, the Falcon 9. Due to weather conditions, the launch was rescheduled for Saturday, May 30, taking two American astronauts to the ISS for the first time in 10 years since the space shuttle retired. This rocket will reconceptualize American spaceflight and catapult our country into the next space exploration era in globally competitive times. The launch will be aired on NASA Live (https://www.nasa.gov/nasalive) as well as major networks.
We are incredibly proud of Matthew and all his accomplishments.

Learn more about Matthew's accomplishments at
https://news.engineering.iastate.edu/2020/04/14/mse-alums-shape-space-technology-future-at-spacex/.

Thank You to Promise of Hope Foundation, RENU Contracting Restoration, and Millburn Flooring for their donation of 3000 masks to Lakeland Families.

The Promise of Hope Foundation, along with RENU Contracting Restoration and Milburn Flooring, launched the campaign “Cover Our Kids.” These organizations donate non-surgical masks that are FDA certified and CE-approved to local communities and school districts.

Lakeland received 3000 masks that were donated to families in need. This week, the masks were distributed to the families at their weekly Lakeland Food Service meal pick up. George Prine, Lakeland's Facilities Director, and his staff coordinated the distribution.

post_text:
A Big Thank You Goes To The Walter Panas Family

Thank you, everyone, in the Walter Panas family, who contributed to the collection for essential workers. The school collected over $650. Through community support, Walter Panas was able to say thank you to many of our local heroes who are protecting us during this difficult time.

The Walter Panas community also sent food to other local heroes. They sent two trays of food from J.V. Bagels to the Mohegan Lake Volunteer Fire Department and Ambulance Corp. Thank you to the Helfrich Family for making the delivery. Some of you may recognize Walter Panas alums, Ryan Piazza and Pat Guida. Additionally, they sent bagels and sandwiches to the Westchester County Police, Hawthorne, and Cortlandt precincts. J.V. Bagels and Britt & Co. Bagels made the deliveries; thank you.

Thank you again to everyone for your contributions.

Feeding Westchester Food Pantry Continues to Help the Lakeland Community

Thank you to Lakeland volunteers and Feeding Westchester for making these much-needed food distributions possible. On May 6, within two hours, food was delivered to over 300 cars. Feeding Westchester and Lakeland volunteers served 625 children, 515 adults, and 59 senior citizens, for a total of 1,199 people.

Superintendent Dr. Stone made sure these food distributions would continue after the schools were closed. Director of Facilities George Prine created a parking lot infrastructure making the car deliveries safer for everyone.

Also, thank you to Jefferson Valley Mall, and Lakeland's Buildings and Grounds crew for supplying and setting up tables and tents.

Thank you, everyone, we appreciate it, and so does our community!

Feeding Westchester and Lakeland volunteers served 625 children, 515 adults, and 59 senior citizens, for a total of 1,199 people.

Superintendent Dr. Stone made sure these food distributions would continue after the schools were closed. Director of Facilities George Prine created a parking lot infrastructure making the car deliveries safer for everyone.

Also, thank you to Jefferson Valley Mall, and Lakeland's Buildings and Grounds crew for supplying and setting up tables and tents.

Thank you, everyone, we appreciate it, and so does our community!

post_text:
I cannot let the day pass without thanking nurses for the tremendous and critical role they serve in our world, and now in particular for all they give so that others can be safe. Over the years I have watched as our school nurses assume more and more responsibilities, not only cleaning bumps and bruises, but managing medications for large populations of students, assessing injuries and concussions, making sure athletes are physically healthy and ready to compete, handling frequent emergencies and even hosting a safe haven for students who turn emotional issues into physical symptoms. The list is endless, as is their dedication.

On behalf of the Lakeland Central School District, thank you to nurses everywhere for everything you do. You are true angels on earth.

Dr. George Stone, Superintendent

Congratulations to Lakeland Copper Beech Middle School's Ronak Das for taking first place in the 2020 Tri-County Science and Engineering Fair which was held online this year.

Patricia Viggiano, the District's Director of Science, reports. "Even through these difficult times, we see our students shine. We had a middle school student compete online at the Tri-County Science and Engineering Fair. The winners were announced April 25."

Das took home first place in the Math/Computer category for his research project titled: Predictive Analytics of COVID-19. He finished in third place last year, the first year the students competed.

This win qualifies him as an alternate for the National Broadcom Masters Competition.

Thanks to Judy Toledano, LCBMS Science Teacher, who runs the middle school science club.

The organization will hold the cards for 72 hours before distributing them.

post_text:
Lakeland CSD Debaters Competed Online
April 08, 2020

Eight debaters from the Lakeland Central School District Debate Team competed in a six-round Georgetown online tournament on Friday, April 3, and Saturday, April 4, from the comfort of their own homes.

Four hundred and fifteen students from 55 schools in 21 states and two countries (Canada, Korea) competed in the event. Alanalee Huges (Panas) and Gurmerha Bawa (Lakeland) finished with a 3-3 record and lost in the first elimination debate, as did Liam Webb (Lakeland) and Jeremy Carbo (Lakeland). Jenna Bashjawish (Lakeland), Izabella Widulski (Lakeland), Edwin Anthony (Lakeland), Ilan Villard (Lakeland), also participated, and Ethan Warren (L) judged Middle School Debates.

Jenna was the tournament’s third-best overall beginner speaker. Ilan and Liam judged part of the middle school elimination debates.

It was a fun challenge to have 110 rooms simultaneously scheduled and rescheduled online throughout the entire weekend. The students are now preparing for an online competition in early May. Congratulations to everyone.

post_text:
Posted March 18, 2020

Lakeland Community,

While we understand how closed in people are feeling and that fresh air can be helpful, this cannot take place on school fields at this time. Schools have been closed by executive order, and that includes our fields as well. Please walk around your neighborhood, ride bikes but do not plan to congregate at the schools. Starting in the next day or two construction will start back up at Lakeland High School and this is another reason we must prohibit pedestrian traffic. The grounds will be posted as they are after hours. I regret deeply having to make these announcements as I know we all love being outside, and I know how much our students miss seeing with their friends. But the directives have been issued, and we all need to respect them. Thank you in advance for your cooperation.

George Stone Superintendent

Be well,
Steve Rappleyea, Psy.D., C.A.S.

Lakeland Central School District

shared_text:
Lakeland Central School District added 6 new photos.
March 2 at 4:09 PM ·

Senator Pete Harckham moderated a student forum and panel discussion at Lakeland High School on Friday, February 28th entitled "Hate in the Age of Multiculturalism". Participants included students from Walter Panas, Lakeland, Peekskill and Mahopac High Schools and Mildred E Strang Middle School. Students were able to ask questions and give comments to both Senator Harckham and the student panelists. "We have to teach and agree upon some common values- kindness, love, tolerance, respect" said Senator Harckham, "And hope that these are enough that they begin to bind us back together."

post_text: Congratulations to the Lakeland/Panas girls 4x200 relay of Taryn Hodge, Lauren Salazar, Makayla Waugh, and JaLia Williams which qualified for the 2020 New York State Public High School Athletic Association’s Indoor Track and Field Championships. The team placed second at the Section 1 State Qualifier in a time of 1:46.43, the relay’s fastest time of the season. The state meet will take place on Saturday, March 7, at the Ocean Breeze Track and Field Facility, on Staten Island. The team of Millie Lichtenwalner-Seabaugh, Waugh, and Williams won the sectional title by running the 4x200 meter relay in a time of 1:47.53. Lauren Salazar rejoined the team for state qualifiers after recovering from an injury. The team is coached by Ryan Johnson. They are the second girls team to go to the state meet following the 2018 relay team which include Salazar.

post_text:
educating our "Shining Stars" Art at the Elementary Schools
Art at the elementary level is a wonderful and unique experience for every student. Every year builds on the one past allowing students to increase their skills over the entire six years. Students in elementary art get to create with multiple mediums, learn about various artists and develop essential lifelong skills. From clay to plaster, paint to oil pastels, from DaVinci to Warhol, elementary art students are taught an appreciation of the arts and how to best bring their imaginations to life.

Fifteen Walter Panas and Lakeland high school student artists are currently on display as part of the Katonah Museum's annual high school art exhibition - Young Artists 2020. Now in its 37th year, this exhibition presents the work of the most talented high school seniors in the region. This year nearly 400 students from 40 schools in Westchester, Putnam, Dutchess and Fairfield counties are participating in Young Artists 2020. The opening reception was held Feb. 9. The art work will be on display through March 1.
http://www.katonahmuseum.org/exhibitions/
Student artists include: Panas: Emma Bate, Rachel Yi, Madison Colombo, Cath Guida, Amaavi Miriyagalla, Christina Miscione, Emily Ramirez, Miranda Marsocci
Lakeland: Selina Bernat, Jule Dimaranan, Julia Dimaranan, Lily McConnell, Macauley Tompkins, Ivy Yang, Leara Morales

post_text:
Students and staff at Lincoln-Titus Elementary School are reading the book Matilda by Roald Dahl for the One School, One Book program.
Throughout the building, students are engaged in "Matilda" activities. Instructional coaches, Mrs. Crivelli and Mrs. Quinn guided a Design Thinking challenge with second grade students. The following problem was discussed, Matilda needs to complete an experiment for Miss Honey. The Trunchbull hid the materials in hopes that Matilda will not be able to complete the experiment, and Miss Honey will be put in the chokey. Matilda used her powers to gather materials to complete the experiment. She is trying to answer the questions, Which material will move the car the furthest? So, Mrs. Crivelli and Mrs. Quinn enlisted the help of the seconders to determine the best material (foam, cardboard, and felt) for the job. The students planned, tested, and modified their experiment to help Matilda.

Congratulations to the Lakeland/Panas/P.V. combined gymnastics team for its Section One Championship. Led by top-10 performances in the vault by Veronica Rosario and Alyssa Limardo; by Catherine Panzanaro, Caitlin Pellegrino and Rosario on the uneven bars; Rosario and the first-place Pellegrino on balance beam and by Rosario in the all-around, the combined squad ended Mahopac’s three-year dominance, winning the Section 1 team championship with 171.6 points.
Qualifying for the NYS Championships were: Panas' Veronica Rosario and LHS' Samantha Flores on the beam. Team members from Putnam Valley HS Caitlin Pellegrino (All Around) and Emily Quinn (Bars) also qualified for the States.

Van Cortlandtville Elementary School students have once again reached out to the help members of their community as part of the ‘Chase the Chill' event.

The students, members of the Grade 5 Leadership team, traveled to North Westchester Restorative Therapy and Nursing Center, a rehabilitation center in Mohegan Lake, where they distributed donated scarves to residents at the center.

For the third year, the school partnered with Valerie Overton Moore and Chase the Chill of Westchester. Overton-Moore provided scarves she had personally made, which were combined with those contributed by the Van Cortlandtville ES community.

Spreading warmth and kindness to the community is the mission of leaders at Van Cortlandtville Elementary School.

post_text:
Walter Panas teacher finds WWII Dog Tags Belonging to a Walter Panas Alumni’s Father
Nicole Amabile, Walter Panas High School teacher, discovered WWII dog tags in a 1912 National cash register drawer located on the property that was once owned by the owner of the dog tags, Willam M. Groark.
He served in the United States Army during WWII.
Nicole was able to get in contact with his son, William J. Groark, Walter Panas High School alumni, Class of 1977. William was elated that Nicole found his father’s tags that mean so much to him and his family. The Groark family owned and operated Hotel Evergreen Manor for many years on this 28 acre Cortlandt Manor property.

AP Physics field trip to Brookhaven Labs on Long Island.

They gathered data for an electron beam being accelerated using a known voltage around a visible (the bright green ring) and measurable circular path using a tunable magnetic field. This data allowed them to discover the charge to mass ratio of the electron.

“The kids left with a sense of wonder and excitement about science in general and research in particular."- Jason Marrero

On Saturday, December 7, Walter Panas High School's UNICEF officers took a trip to the city to volunteer at the World’s Big Sleep-out, a nationwide event to raise awareness to homelessness and raise funds for homeless outreach charities worldwide.

During a 6 hour shift, the club's officers helped run registration and information at the heart of Time’s Square and made connections with several UNICEF USA officers also stationed at the event. Through social media, we are now just beginning to see the full impact of the event, with 50,000 participants worldwide and close to $25 million in donations and sponsorships.

post_text: New York State Senator Peter Harckman stopped by Van Cortandtville Elementary School recently to witness the results of a grant from the his office. The indoor gym equipment was installed recently using a portion of the $25,000 grant. The equipment purchased is being used to enhance the educational environment for the building's special needs population, in particular, and is being used by all students. The remaining funds from the grant will be used to aid in the reconstruction of the school's outdoor playground.

post_text:
A Lakeland Education Foundation grant has helped bring books alive for eighth graders at Lakeland Copper Beech Middle School. Neal Shusterman, a popular young adult author, spent the day with the 8th graders recently.

“It was a day filled with inspiration, conversation, and collaboration,” said Janice Reichert, one of the 8th grade English teachers who wrote the grant. His books include the series Arc of a Scythe which many students started reading at the end of last year.

The books include Scythe (2016), Thunderhead (2018) and the latest The Toll (2019). That book was released the day he appeared at the middle school and students were able to get copies of the book at a discounted price and have them autographed.

Read more about Shusterman's visit at:
http://www.lakelandschools.org/news_detail_T5_R964.php

Lakeland High School Field Hockey secured their place in the New York State Class B final four for the 11th consecutive year with a 3-0 victory over Section 9's Rondout Valley in the Regional finals held Saturday at Lakeland High School.
Mia Smith opened the scoring at 15:53 of the first half. Nancy Pagliorli scored the second with an assist by Emma Halderman at 2:59 of the first. Lakeland was up 2-0 at half.
Jenna McCrudden added the third goal at 24:36 of the second half.
Lakeland plays in the state semifinal on Saturday November 16 at 3:00 pm at Williamsville High School (outside of Buffalo).

post_text:
In an effort to raise awareness about hunger in the local community, Lakeland Copper Beech Middle School held their third annual Empty Bowls Dinner on October 4.

Students researched hunger, made posters and place mats and made food for the event, as then created ceramic bowls that attendees were able to take home at the end of the evening in exchange for a donation. The event was organized by Art teacher Eileen Rosenkampff and Consumer Science teacher Christina Connors.

“Students have a better awareness of their contribution to the issue when we think about things like the amount of food that gets thrown out in the cafeteria that could potentially be going to help people in our community instead of going in the garbage. Students will begin to recognize their role in what’s going on.” Connors said.

The Empty Bowls Dinner is part of a national organization called the Empty Bowls Project. The proceeds from this year’s event went to support Fred’s Food Pantry in Peekskill, NY.
